sity, Moorhead]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 1963\u20131969\n|unit          = [[Army National Guard]]\n}}\n'''Collin Clark Peterson''' (born June 29, 1944) is an American politician, member of the [[Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party]] and the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MN|7}}, serving since 1991. He is the ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on Agriculture|House Committee on Agriculture]] and the dean of the [[United States congressional delegations from Minnesota|Minnesota congressional delegation]]. A conservative Democrat, his district, Minnesota's largest and most rural district, includes most of the western area of the state, including [[Moorhead, Minnesota|Moorhead]], [[Fergus Falls]], [[Bemidji]], [[Detroit Lakes]], [[Thief River Falls]], [[Willmar]], [[Marshall, Minnesota|Marshall]], and [[Alexandria, Minnesota|Alexandria]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nCollin Peterson was born in [[Fargo, North Dakota]], grew up on a farm in [[Baker, Minnesota]], and received his B.A. at [[Minnesota State University Moorhead]].\n\nPeterson was a member of the [[Minnesota Senate]] for the [[Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party]] (the Minnesota branch of the Democratic Party) from 1977 to 1986, representing a district in northwestern Minnesota. In 1976, he defeated Republican nominee [[Frank DeGroat]] 55%-45%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=748811 |title=MN State Senate 10 Race - Nov 02, 1976 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1982, he won re-election against State Representative [[Cal Larson]] by just 200 votes, or 0.8% difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=432458 |title=MN State Senate 10 Race - Nov 02, 1982 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1980s\nIn 1984, he ran for [[Minnesota's 7th congressional district]] in Northwestern Minnesota, held by Republican [[Arlan Stangeland]]. Peterson lost 57%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=51846 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 06, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1986, he ran in a rematch and narrowly lost by just 121 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38470 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 04, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1988, he ran again but lost in the DFL primary to State Senator [[Marv Hanson]] 55%\u201345%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=429185 |title=MN District 7 - DFL Primary Race - Sep 13, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> Hanson went on to lose to Stangeland 55%\u201345%.\n\n;1990s\nIn 1990, he ran for a fourth time and won the primary. In the general election, he finally defeated seven-term incumbent Stangeland by 54%\u201346%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=34098 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1992, he narrowly won re-election by a 50%\u201349% margin against former State Representative Bernie Omann.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28028 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In a 1994 rematch, Peterson won again by a 51%\u201349% margin, despite the [[Republican Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28913 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In 1996, he won re-election with 68% of the vote, and won every county in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29552 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-01-15}}</ref> In 1998, he won re-election with 72% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30698 |title=MN District 7 Race - Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2000s\nIn the 2000s, Peterson never faced a serious re-election challenge and only once did he win re-election with less than two-thirds of the vote. In 2000, he was mentioned as a possible candidate [[United States Senate election in Minnesota, 2000|for the U.S. Senate]] against Republican [[Rod Grams]], but he chose to run for re-election, winning with 69% of the vote.<ref name=snapshot>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/2004/campaign/congress/peterson/|title=Collin Peterson|publisher=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]|date=2004|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2002, he won with 65% of the vote. In 2004, he won with 66% of the vote. In 2006, he won with 70% of the vote. In 2008, he won with 72% of the vote.\n\n;2010s\nIn 2010, Peterson survived another Republican wave election. This time, he defeated Lee Byberg 55%\u201338%, his worst election performance since 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=496785 |title=MN - District 07 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> In [[United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2012#District 7|2012]], Peterson won re-election with 60.38% to Republican Lee Byberg's 34.85% and Independent Adam Steele's 4.67%.\n\nIn 2013, Republicans began pressuring Peterson, in hopes of convincing him to retire. His seat is one of only a handful that is represented by a Democrat but was carried by [[Mitt Romney]] in the 2012 election and is seen as a top pick-up opportunity should Peterson retire. Their tactics included airing television advertisements, hiring a press staffer to give opposition research to reporters, hiring a tracker to follow him around his district and record him, and sending [[mobile billboard]]s with critical statements on them to drive around his hometown. Peterson responded by saying \"They don't have anybody else to go after. It's kind of ridiculous, but whatever.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/columns/polinaut/archive/2013/05/gop_pokes_at_pe.shtml |title=GOP pokes at Peterson on healthcare and the IRS |publisher=MPR News |date=28 May 2013 |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/columns/on-the-trail/parties-push-for-house-retirements-20130523 |title=Parties Push For House Retirements |publisher=National Journal |date=23 May 2013 |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref> After Republicans spread rumors that Peterson was planning to buy a house in Florida and retire there, he said: \"I went from neutral on running again to 90 percent just because of this stupid stuff they're doing. You can't let these people be in charge of anything, in my opinion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/columns/polinaut/archive/2013/06/peterson_says_g.shtml3 |title=Peterson says GOP efforts to push him out having the opposite effect |publisher=MPR News |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=10 June 2013 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On March 17, 2014, Peterson officially announced that he was running for re-election, saying, \"I still have a lot of work to do\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/250560221.html |title=Democratic U.S. Rep. Collin Peterson will run again |publisher=Star Tribune |date=March 17, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2014}}</ref> Despite being heavily targeted by national Republican groups, Peterson defeated Republican State Senator [[Torrey Westrom]] in the general election by 54% to 46%.\n\nIn January 2015, Peterson stated that he is \"running at this point\" for re-election in 2016, saying that the efforts by Republicans to unseat him had \"energized me\" and \"got me fired up\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/statelocal/289930241.html|title=Rep. Collin Peterson: I am planning on running again next year|work=startribune.com|accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, he said that he may keep running until 2020 because the Republicans \"made me mad\" with their efforts to defeat him or persuade him to retire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/allisonsherry/status/526809821044305920|title= @collinpeterson said he may run til 2020 cuz the Republicans 'made me mad'|work=Twitter|author=Allison Sherry|date=October 27, 2014|accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nPeterson was one of the original founders of the [[Blue Dog Coalition]], the [[Congressional caucus|caucus]] of House Democrats who identify as moderates and conservatives.<ref>{{cite book |last=Certain |first=Geni |title=Professor-Politician, The Biography of Alabama Congressman Glen Browder |publisher=NewSouth Books |year=2012 |page=147 |isbn=978-1-58838-254-2}}</ref> He is one of the most conservative Democrats in Congress and frequently crosses the party line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2009/07/29/peterson-gop|title=GOP targets U.S. Rep. Collin Peterson|publisher=MPR News|author=Tim Nelson|date=July 29, 2009|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=defectors>{{cite web|url=http://www.prospect.org/web/page.ww?section=root&name=ViewPrint&articleId=10306 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416105551/http://www.prospect.org/web/page.ww?section=root&name=ViewPrint&articleId=10306 |title=The Defectors |publisher=Prospect.org |date=October 5, 2005 |archivedate=April 16, 2007 |accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=sobig>{{cite web|url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/campaign2002/ap_7dist.shtml|title=7th District so big, candidates use planes like cars |publisher=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]|date=October 14, 2002|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=aftermarriage>{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2013/06/27/news/doma-politicians-move-on|title=After marriage ruling, many Minnesota politicians eager to move on|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|date=June 27, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/collin-peterson-torrey-westrom-minnesota-7/|title=Peterson\u2019s Greatest Challenge Yet, but GOP Still Looks to 2016|publisher=Roll Call|author=Colin Diersing|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=November 2, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/203863421.html|title=Republicans make U.S. Rep. Collin Peterson an early target|publisher=Star Tribune|date=June 27, 2013|accessdate=November 2, 2006}}</ref> In 2008, a report by [[Congressional Quarterly]] found he had the lowest party loyalty score over the previous five years of any member of the Minnesota congressional delegation.<ref name=UMN2008>{{cite web|url=http://blog.lib.umn.edu/cspg/smartpolitics/2008/10/election_profile_minnesotas_7t.php|title=Election Profile: Minnesota's 7th Congressional District (2008)|publisher=Humphrey School of Public Affairs|author=Eric Ostermeier|date=October 26, 2008|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref> In the [[109th United States Congress|109th Congress]], he was rated 50% conservative by a conservative group<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressional Voting Scorecard 2005 |work=SBE Council\u2019s Congressional Voting Scorecard 2005 |publisher=Small Business & Entrepreneurship Council |date=June 2006 |url=http://www.sbecouncil.org/uploads/Ratings2005Scorecard.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=November 2, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929121518/http://www.sbecouncil.org/uploads/Ratings2005Scorecard.pdf |archivedate=September 29, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref> and 57% [[Progressivism|progressive]] by a liberal group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leading with the Left|publisher=Progressive Punch|url=http://www.progressivepunch.org|accessdate=November 2, 2006}}</ref>\n\nPeterson is generally conservative on social issues; he strongly opposes abortion and has been one of the few Democrats to vote against embryonic stem cell research.<ref name=snapshot/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/29-stem-cell-debate-to-spill-over-into-06 |title=Stem-cell debate to spill over into '06 |publisher=The Hill |date=May 26, 2005 |accessdate=September 13, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920051803/https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/29-stem-cell-debate-to-spill-over-into-06 |archivedate=September 20, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> He has voted to ban physician assisted suicide and also to approve the proposed [[Flag Desecration Amendment]] to the [[United States Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twincities.com/mld/twincities/news/legislature/12053882.htm|title=Dayton stands firm on flag issue|publisher=St. Paul Pioneer Press|date=July 5, 2005|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref> He also voted for the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] and supports the death penalty.<ref name=snapshot/><ref name=aftermarriage/>\n\nThe 7th contains some of the most conservative counties in the state and also the state's most rural district; many DFLers outside the Twin Cities are hunters and trappers who oppose gun control.<ref name=sobig/><ref name=UMN2008/> Peterson is a conservationist, but opposes \"excessive environmental regulation\" because he argues they harm farmers.<ref name=sobig/> He is an avid hunter and supports [[animal trapping]], but in 2000 he joined with [[The Humane Society of the United States]] to pass legislation that stopped the interstate shipping of birds for [[cockfight]]ing.<ref name=snapshot/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/01/news/mn-14881|title=Strange Allies Battle Against Cockfighting|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=April 1, 2000|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref> He has an \"A\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association]] and is a \"staunch\" supporter of gun rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twincities.com/ci_22234039/u-s-rep-peterson-opposes-new-ban-assault |title=U.S. Rep. Collin Peterson opposes new ban on assault weapons |publisher=St. Paul Pioneer Press |date=December 20, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he's been called a strong fiscal conservative,<ref name=UMN2008/> he is somewhat closer to the liberal wing of his party on economic issues: he has voted against most [[free trade]] agreements, the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]],<ref name=sobig/> the [[Freedom to Farm Act]], and the [[Telecommunications Act of 1996]]. He also voted against both versions of the [[Patriot Act]] and he has been sharply critical of the [[No Child Left Behind Act]], which he contends is unfair to rural students.<ref name=defectors/><ref name=sobig/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald-journal.com/government/election/2008/mcleod/us-representative-district-7.html |title=Two candidates seek to represent US District 7 |publisher=Herald-Journal |date=2008|accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> He supports the [[FairTax]], a national sales tax, estate-tax repeal, tort reform, and the [[Bush tax cuts]]. He voted against the [[Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act]].<ref name=defectors/>\n\nPeterson joined the House Republicans in voting against the [[Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993]].<ref name=defectors/>\n\nIn 1998, as part of an effort to change what were considered unequal fishing regulations between the U.S. and Canada, Peterson gained attention by proposing a [[constitutional amendment]] that would allow the residents of Minnesota's [[Northwest Angle]] to vote on whether they wanted to [[secession|secede]] from the United States and join the Canadian province of [[Manitoba]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.walrusmagazine.com/articles/2011.01-history-the-lost-canadians/ |title=The Lost Canadians |last=Stoddard |first=Grant |publisher=The Walrus |date=January\u2013February 2011 |pages=24\u201331}}</ref> Peterson said that the amendment, which was part of a mock secession movement, was successful in bringing the issue to the attention of the White House: \"In just the day after I introduced (the amendment), people from the vice president's office have been asking questions, people in the White House (too). I've got meetings scheduled with the U.S. trade representative... we've educated people on both sides of the border, and I think we've brought it closer to the point where we'll get this thing resolved.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-03-21/news/9803210102_1_northwest-angle-fishing-canadian-embassy|title=Fishing Dispute Has Territory In Minnesota Angling To Secede|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=David Brauer|date=March 21, 1998|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he was one of just 16 Democrats to vote for President Bush's [[Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act]].<ref name=defectors/>\n\nFrom 2003 through 2005, $14.7&nbsp;billion in crop subsidies went to the congressional districts of members on the House Committee on Agriculture, an analysis by the non-partisan Environmental Working Group found. That was 42.4% of the total subsidies. Peterson is reported to have brought $874&nbsp;million to his District.<ref>Dilanian, Ken, [http://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2007-07-25-farmbill_N.htm#subsidies \" Billions go to House panel members' districts\"], USA Today. July 26, 2007.</ref> In Peterson's district, which includes sugar beets, wheat and poultry, 58% of the $2.8&nbsp;billion paid out in crop subsidies from 1995 to 2005 went to 10% of recipients, according to the Environmental Working Group, which tracks farm spending. The chairman says he has no problem with that. \"Ten percent of the farmers produce 90% of the food,\" he says.\n\nIn 2004, he joined with [[Minnesota Attorney General]] [[Mike Hatch]] in suing the state of [[North Dakota]] over what they argued were discriminatory laws that forbid non-North Dakota residents from hunting during the first week of the [[waterfowl hunting]] [[Hunting season|season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/2004/03/09_ap_huntingsuit/|title=Minnesota suing North Dakota over hunting laws|publisher=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]|author=Laura McCallum|date=March 9, 2004|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref> Their case was rejected by the [[United States District Court for the District of North Dakota]], a decision which was upheld by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-8th-circuit/1144577.html|title=Minnesota Hatch v. Hoeven|publisher=[[FindLaw]]|date=August 3, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2005, he was selected by the House Democratic Caucus to succeed former Texas Congressman [[Charlie Stenholm]] as the Ranking Member on the [[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]. He became the committee's chairman after the Democrats won control of the House two years later.\n\nPeterson was a cosponsor of the Agricultural Job Opportunities, Benefits, and Security Act of 2005<ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h109-884 H.R. 884: Agricultural Job Opportunities, Benefits, and Security Act of 2005], GovTrack.us</ref><ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c109:S.359: Bill Text 109th Congress (2005\u20132006) S.359.IS], ''[[THOMAS]]''</ref> which would provide job protection for three million illegal immigrant agricultural workers and their families, and extend the visas of legal immigrant agricultural workers.\n\nIn December 2005, Peterson joined four Republicans to form the [[Second Amendments]], a rock and [[country music|country]] band.<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/collin-peterson-mn/ Minnesota District 7:Rep. Collin Peterson (D)]</ref>\n\nAlong with John Conyers, in April 2006 Peterson brought an action against George W. Bush and others alleging violations of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] in the passing of the [[Deficit Reduction Act of 2005]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory?id=1898817 |title=11 House Members to Sue Over Budget Bill |date=April 27, 2006 |accessdate=February 20, 2007 |work=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205095203/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory?id=1898817 |archivedate=February 5, 2009 }}</ref> The case (''[[Conyers v. Bush]]'') was ultimately dismissed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=2633701 |title=Judge Dismisses Budget Bill Lawsuit |date=November 6, 2006 |accessdate=November 28, 2006 |work=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203215630/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=2633701 |archivedate=February 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nPeterson was one of the few Democrats to vote in favor of the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2006-491 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H.R. 6166 [109th&#93;: Military Commissions Act of 2006 |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=September 27, 2006 |accessdate=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Peterson was the lone [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to vote against the Federal Price Gouging Prevention Act.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2007/roll404.xml |title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 404 |date=May 23, 2007 |accessdate=May 24, 2007 |work=House of Representatives Roll Call |author=Clerk of the House of Representatives}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2009, Peterson was amongst the seven Democrats who voted in the House together with the unanimous Republican opposition against President Obama's stimulus package ([[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll046.xml |title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 46 on \"Making supplemental appropriations for fiscal year ending 2009\" |date=January 28, 2009 |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |work=House of Representatives Roll Call |author=Clerk of the House of Representatives}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/congress/38731832.html?elr=KArks8c7PaP3E77K_3c::D3aDhU6:_0c:QyDiiUiacyKUU |title=Rep. Peterson: Stimulus is flawed |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |work=Star Tribune |author=Kevin D\u00edaz}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, Peterson voted against the [[Matthew Shepard and James Byrd, Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act]].<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll223.xml]. Retrieved February 21, 2014.</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2009, Peterson voiced his opposition to [[climate change]] legislation proposed by the [[Obama Administration]] saying, \"I will not support any kind of climate change bill \u2013 even if you fix this \u2013 because I don't trust anybody anymore. I've had it.\" Peterson predicted that an [[Environmental Protection Agency]] proposal to assess indirect effects of ethanol production on greenhouse gas emissions, combined with the climate change legislation, could \"kill off [[corn ethanol]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.feedstuffs.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=F4D1A9DFCD974EAD8CD5205E15C1CB42&nm=Breaking+News&type=news&mod=News&mid=A3D60400B4204079A76C4B1B129CB433&tier=3&nid=2ED25D0552384C0396608AE0F548F8E9 |title=Peterson cries foul on EPA ethanol proposal, vows not to support climate change bill |date=May 6, 2009 |accessdate=May 7, 2009 |work=Feedstuffs |author=Sally Schuff}}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2009, a controversy erupted after Peterson was quoted in a [[Politico.com]] article saying, \"25 percent of my people believe the Pentagon and [[Donald Rumsfeld|Rumsfeld]] [[9/11 Truth|were responsible for]] [[September 11, 2001 attacks|taking the twin towers down]]. That's why I don't do town meetings.\" The state Republican Party denounced the remark as \"outrageous and offensive\". Peterson apologized for the comment, which he described as \"off-hand\".<ref name=\"strib\">{{cite web |title=Peterson apologizes for slap at constituents |first=Eric |last=Roper |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/51861647.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUUT |date=July 29, 2009 |accessdate=July 28, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2010, Peterson voted against the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Peterson Statement on Health Care Vote |date=Mar 21, 2010 |url=http://collinpeterson.house.gov/press/111th/Peterson%20Statement%20on%20Health%20Care%20Vote.html |accessdate=Mar 25, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325165314/http://collinpeterson.house.gov:80/press/111th/Peterson%20Statement%20on%20Health%20Care%20Vote.html |archivedate=March 25, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he was endorsed by the [[National Right to Life Committee]]<ref>[http://stoptheabortionagenda.com/2010/10/18/national-right-to-life-pac-endorses-chip-cravaack-for-congress-in-minnesota-8th-congressional-district/ National Right to Life PAC Endorses Chip Cravaack for Congress in Minnesota 8th Congressional District] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706123323/http://stoptheabortionagenda.com/2010/10/18/national-right-to-life-pac-endorses-chip-cravaack-for-congress-in-minnesota-8th-congressional-district/ |date=July 6, 2011 }}</ref> and the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Andy |last=Birkey |url=http://minnesotaindependent.com/71742/national-rifle-association-endorses-walz |title=National Rifle Association endorses Walz |publisher=The Minnesota Independent |date=October 4, 2010 |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218220845/http://minnesotaindependent.com/71742/national-rifle-association-endorses-walz |archivedate=December 18, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he co-sponsored HR 3, the No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act.<ref name=\"HR3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h112-3 |title=Full text of House Resolution 3: No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act |publisher=Govtrack.us |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> The bill contained an exception for \"forcible rape,\" which opponents criticized as potentially excluding drug-facilitated rape, date rape, and other forms of rape.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/postpartisan/2011/02/what_is_forcible_rape_exactly.html | work=The Washington Post | title=What is 'forcible rape' exactly?}}</ref> The bill also allowed an exception for minors who are victims of incest.<ref name=\"HR3\"/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n;Current\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]''' (beginning with the 102nd Congress to present day; see: {{USBill|102|HRes|43}}<ref>Other sessions include the \"107th Congress (2001-2002) H.RES.25.EH\"</ref>) \n** Ranking Member & ''former'' Chairman.<ref>Peterson has also been the Chairman at least three times: \n* {{USBill|112|HRes|7}}: 112th Congress (2011-2012) H.RES.7.EH , \n* {{USBill|111|HRes|8}}: 111th Congress (2009-2010) H.RES.8.EH and \n* {{USBill|110|HRes|7}}: 110th Congress (2007-2008) H.RES.7.EH \n* but not in the 109th Congress.</ref> As ranking member of the full committee, Peterson may sit as an ''ex officio'' member of all subcommittees.\n\n;Previous\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** This was one of the first committees Peterson served on {102nd<ref>{{USBill|102|HRes|43}}: 102nd Congress (1991-1992) H.RES.43.ATH</ref> 103rd<ref>{{USBill|103|HRes|34}}: 103rd Congress (1993-1994) H.RES.34.EH</ref> 104th<ref>{{USBill|104|HRes|31}}: 104th Congress (1995-1996) H.RES.31.EH</ref> & 105th<ref>{{USBill|105|HRes|13}}: 105th Congress (1997-1998) H.RES.13.EH</ref> Congresses}. It ''appears'' that he did not serve on this committee from the 106th onwards.\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|Veterans' Affairs Committee]]'''\n** Began membership in the 106th Congress,<ref>{{USBill|106|HRes|7}}: 106th Congress (1999-2000) H.RES.7.ATH</ref> 107th.<ref>107th Congress (2001-2002) H.RES.25.EH</ref>\n\n===Caucus membership===\n*Military Veterans Caucus, Co-chair\n\n==Electoral history==\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2014#District 7}}\n{{Election box begin|title=2014 Seventh Congressional District of Minnesota Elections}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Collin Peterson\n  |votes      = 130,546\n  |percentage = 54.21%\n  |change     = -6.2%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Torrey Westrom\n  |votes      = 109,955\n  |percentage = 45.66%\n  |change     = +10.9%}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2012#District 7}}\n  \n{{Election box begin|title=2012 Seventh Congressional District of Minnesota Elections}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Collin Peterson\n  |votes      = 197,791\n  |percentage = 60.38%\n  |change     = +5.2%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Lee Byberg\n  |votes      = 114,151\n  |percentage = 34.85%\n  |change     = -2.8%}}\n\n{{Election box ca